<SitePage
  title="How PAI works — PAI"
  description="PAI is a bootable Linux OS on a USB drive. It runs local AI models without touching your computer's disk, leaves no trace, and works offline."
  active="how"
>
  <article class="how">
    <header class="how-hero">
      <h1>How PAI works</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        PAI is a complete operating system on a USB drive. You plug it in,
        boot from it, and run a private AI workstation. When you're done,
        you shut down, pull out the USB, and the computer is exactly how
        you found it.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="how-section">
      <h2>1. It's a separate operating system</h2>
      <p>
        PAI is Debian Linux with a privacy-focused desktop and local AI tools
        pre-installed. It runs entirely from the USB drive — your installed
        Windows, macOS, or Linux is never touched. Your hard drive isn't
        mounted unless you explicitly ask for it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="how-section">
      <h2>2. AI runs locally, not in the cloud</h2>
      <p>
        PAI ships with <a href="https://ollama.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Ollama</a>
        and a chat UI. Models like Llama, Mistral, and Phi run directly on your
        hardware. No API keys, no accounts, no requests leaving your machine.
      </p>
      <p>
        For conversations that don't need the internet, PAI doesn't need the
        internet. You can unplug ethernet and turn off Wi-Fi — the AI keeps working.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="how-section">
      <h2>3. It leaves no trace by default</h2>
      <p>
        Everything runs in RAM. When you shut down, the memory is wiped and
        the session is gone. No browser history, no cookies, no cached files
        on the host computer.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you <em>want</em> to keep data across sessions (models, chats, notes,
        keys), PAI offers an encrypted persistent volume on the USB drive itself.
        You set the passphrase; without it the data is unreadable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="how-section">
      <h2>4. Network is hardened</h2>
      <p>
        The firewall denies all inbound traffic by default. MAC addresses are
        randomized on every boot. Tor is built in and one-click to enable for
        the whole session.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="how-section">
      <h2>5. You own the stack</h2>
      <p>
        PAI is free software under the GPLv3. The build scripts, hooks, and
        packages are all public. You can audit the image, build your own,
        or fork it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://docs.pai.direct/architecture/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Read the full architecture docs →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="how-cta">
      <a href="/install" class="cta-btn">Install PAI →</a>
    </div>
  </article>

